Date: Sun, 28 Sep 2003
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Canadian Press, 23 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://www.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Canada/2003/09/23/200741-cp.html>


Canadian BSE proposals welcomed by international standards group: negotiator
--------------------------------------------------
Alarmed by the impact that one case of mad cow disease has had on
Canada's beef industry, other countries are embracing Canadian
proposals that would prevent such single cases from wreaking havoc
elsewhere.

Brian Evans, a Canadian representative at the Office Internationale
des Epizooties (OIE) meeting this week in Paris, said nobody wants to
go through what Canada has suffered over the past few months.
"Countries are definitely concerned," Evans said Tuesday. "If they
are next, they want to be treated differently than we've been
treated."

Evans is in the middle of a 5-day conference of the OIE, which sets
international standards on animal health for bodies such as the World
Trade Organization.

The Canadian delegation is pushing for changes to international
protocols for dealing with bovine spongiform encephalopathy, also
known as mad cow disease.

Discovery of one animal with the disease in May 2003 in northern
Alberta closed borders around the world to Canadian beef, costing the
industry more than 1 billion Canadian dollars.

Initial reaction to the Canadian proposals has been good, said Evans.
"It's been a very positive response," he said.

[Byline: Bob Weber]

******
[4]
Date: Sun, 28 Sep 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CALGARY.CBC.CA News, 25 Sep 2003 [edited]
<http://calgary.cbc.ca/regional/servlet/View?filename=ca_madcow20030925>


Source of mad cow may never be known
------------------------------------
Scientists may never know how an Alberta cow got BSE, but they've
narrowed it to 2 possible explanations.

Health Canada has determined that the animal infected with mad cow
disease didn't contract it from its parents. That means it either got
bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) from something it ate -- the
most common source -- or spontaneously. However, there isn't enough
left of the diseased cow's brain to be able to test whether it
occurred spontaneously.

The finding was released Thursday at a conference of international
experts on mad cow disease and related illnesses.

"One aspect of the explanation of the disease has been ruled out, and
what I think it tends to do is support the working assumption that it
was an infectious case," Dr. Michael Coulthart, head of the Health
Canada lab that tests for BSE, said.

Most cattle contract BSE when they eat the remains of another
infected cow. The remains of cattle were once used in cattle feed,
but that practice has been banned. Were scientists able to prove that
it was a spontaneous case, meaning little likelihood of other
infected animals, then international borders should open to Canadian
beef.

The province and Health Canada announced 20 May 2003 that a single
case of mad cow disease had been found, and while 2700 cattle were
slaughtered and tested for BSE, it remains the only case to date.

34 countries closed their borders to Canadian beef, costing the
industry an estimated 11 million Canadian dollars a day. The U.S.
and Mexico have since partially re-opened their borders, accepting
boneless cuts of meat from animals younger than 30 months.

The disease only appears in animals older than 2.5 years.

--
